## Chef's Note

French-style scrambled eggs are the opposite of the diner approach -- low heat, constant stirring, and patience produce curds so small and creamy they resemble a savory custard. The key is never letting the pan get too hot. Pulling the pan on and off the heat every 20-30 seconds prevents overcooking, and stirring in cold butter and creme fraiche at the very end halts the cooking while adding richness. These eggs should look slightly underdone when you plate them; residual heat finishes the job.

## Directions

1.  **Crack and Season:** Crack eggs into a cold nonstick skillet (do not whisk in a bowl first). Add butter and salt directly to the pan.
2.  **Cook Low and Slow:** Set the heat to medium-low. Begin stirring immediately with a rubber spatula, breaking the yolks and moving them constantly across the bottom and sides of the pan. After 30 seconds, pull the pan off the heat for 10 seconds, continuing to stir. Return to heat. Repeat this on-and-off pattern for 5-7 minutes. The curds should form very slowly and stay small and creamy.
3.  **Finish:** When the eggs are about 80% set -- still visibly wet and glossy but no longer liquid -- remove the pan from heat completely. Stir in the creme fraiche and a final grind of black pepper. The residual heat will continue to set the eggs.
4.  **Serve:** Transfer immediately to warmed plates. Scatter with chives. Serve with buttered toast or alongside avocado toast. Do not let them sit in the pan -- they will overcook in under a minute.
